<subSubSection id="88916555ED4C7D68BC5FF5D7C3E87B51" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C03436DEED4C7D68BC5FF5D7C3E87B51" blockId="17.[2078,2673,2491,2919]" pageId="17" pageNumber="98">
The recently described 
<taxonomicName id="078B4D5DED4C7D68BDD1F5D7C1397A1D" authorityName="Darvish &amp; Hosseinie" authorityYear="2005" box="[2448,2576,2570,2603]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Jaculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="thaleri">J. thaleri</taxonomicName>
by J. Darvish and F. Hosseinie in 2005 seems to be an aberrant phenotype ofJ. 
<taxonomicName id="078B4D5DED4C7D68BDBEF584C1587A4C" authorityName="Murray" authorityYear="1884" box="[2559,2673,2649,2682]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Dipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="blanfordi">blanfordi</taxonomicName>
rather than an independent species. Based on morphology, 
<taxonomicName id="078B4D5DED4C7D68BD43F575C2BC7AFF" authorityName="Murray" authorityYear="1884" box="[2306,2453,2728,2761]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Dipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="blanfordi">J. blanfordi</taxonomicName>
was considered as a member of subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="078B4D5DED4C7D68BDD8F512C1387AC6" authorityName="Brandt" authorityYear="1844" box="[2457,2577,2767,2800]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Haltomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Haltomys</taxonomicName>
, but it genetically occupies the basal position in the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="078B4D5DED4C7D68BCB5F4C3C2717B09" authorityName="Erxleben" authorityYear="1777" box="[2292,2392,2846,2879]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Jaculus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="17" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Jaculus</taxonomicName>
. Three subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
